Beijing&#39;s natural ecology continues to improve, attracting more than 500 species of wild animals to &quot;settle&quot; in the city - China News Service
2020-07-26 05:03:17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The capital’s natural ecology continues to improve, attracting wild animals to “settle” in the city
There are more than 500 species of wild animals in Beijing
Report from our newspaper (Reporter Wang Bin) A reporter from Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Landscaping and Greening Bureau that in recent years, as the natural ecological environment of the capital continues to improve, the types and numbers of wild animals have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals inhabiting Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including national first-level protected animals such as brown-eared pheasants and black storks, as well as national second-level protected animals such as gorals, whooper swans, gray cranes, and mandarin ducks.
Whether it is planted in urban forests everywhere within the Second Ring Road or in small wetlands embedded between buildings, it not only brings the wild charm of nature to the citizens of the capital, but also attracts wild animals to &quot;settle&quot; in the city.
In midsummer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is full of life.
A raccoon dog was playing leisurely next to a mountain stream, while two badgers were playing with each other.
Looking back, I saw a wild boar that couldn&#39;t help but scratch the bark of a tree. Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Management Office, said that as of the end of 2019, in this green sea with a total area of more than 6,200 hectares, there were living species including the golden eagle, a national first-level protected animal, and the spoon pheasant and goral, a national second-level protected animal. There are 178 species of wild animals in the park, and nearly one-third of the city’s wild animal species can be seen here.
&quot;In Songshan, wild animals are the real &#39;owners&#39;, and our staff can only be regarded as their &#39;bodyguards&#39; at best.&quot;
Hu Qiaoli said that in order to understand the situation of wild animals and plants in the reserve on the spot, more than 30 professional rangers patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and there is also a &quot;big circle&quot; every month. It took a full day to cover almost the entire reserve.
&quot;During inspections, we not only check and record biodiversity, but also check and install artificial bird nests, rescue injured wild animals, install field infrared cameras, etc.&quot;
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wild animals in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli introduced that as the biodiversity of the reserve has continued to enrich in recent years, more and more wild animals have appeared in the camera. Leopard cats, raccoon dogs and pig badgers have become &quot;resident guests&quot;, and the goral, a national second-level protected animal, has The &quot;appearance rate&quot; is also getting higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Department of the Beijing Municipal Landscaping Bureau, said that the number of terrestrial vertebrate wild animals in Beijing has increased from 461 species in 1994 to more than 500 species now. The types and numbers of wild animals in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years. .
The sight of wild animals in cities is becoming more and more common, which is closely related to the continuous upgrading of greening in the capital city in recent years.
In particular, the new round of afforestation and greening construction of one million acres starting in 2018 proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological functions of woodlands and green spaces, and highlight the concept of &quot;close to nature&quot;.
The planning strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green spaces to facilitate wild animals to &quot;visit relatives and friends&quot;. The trees planted are also plants that are favorite nectar and food sources for animals.
Agricultural modernization is &quot;sown&quot; in black soil - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26th: Agricultural modernization is &quot;planted&quot; in black soil
In midsummer, two pesticide-spraying planes flew over the 10,000-acre high-yield demonstration field at the second operation station of the fifth management area of Youyi Farm, forming two white lines. The &quot;first in the world&quot; was planted with black rice seedlings in the green field. Several large characters are particularly eye-catching.
Kong Lingqiang, the director of this operation station, said that this kind of aircraft can spray pesticides on more than 6,000 acres of cultivated land in a day, and its efficiency is about 8 times that of drones and hundreds of times that of manual labor.
This farm is located in Youyi County, Heilongjiang Province, my country&#39;s largest grain-producing province. From the &quot;swish&quot; sound of rice harvesting in the past to the &quot;rumble&quot; sound of motors today, traditional Chinese farming and farming have undergone transformation in this black soil belt.
In addition to aircraft, satellites are also used in modern agricultural production at Youyi Farm.
Kong Lingqiang said that on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to achieve precise fertilization, reduce agricultural input and reduce pollution; on the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the standardization of agricultural machinery in the field.
During this year&#39;s rice production, the farm expanded the operating area of satellite navigation driverless rice transplanting technology from 3,000 acres last year to 30,000 acres.
This technology enables seedlings to be planted more evenly, maximizes the utilization of sunlight and cultivated land resources, and saves labor costs of 16 yuan per acre.
Farms are experimenting with new technologies such as informatization and intelligence in agricultural production, forming my country&#39;s largest agricultural machinery group from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, there are currently 49,000 agricultural machines in the farm, and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field reaches 99.8%.
Agricultural machinery operations achieve 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision sowing in dry fields, and 100% high-horsepower locomotive operations in dry fields.
“Green agriculture, smart agriculture, and digital agriculture are the directions for exploring agricultural modernization.”
Liu Hualian, director of Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization lies in scientific and technological progress.
Heilongjiang Agricultural Reclamation, represented by farms, has played a demonstration and leading role in modern large-scale agriculture in recent years, and has initially established a modern agricultural industry system dominated by large-scale planting, standardized production, and industrialized management.
In the suburbs of Youyi County, there is an agricultural machinery expo park covering an area of 350,000 square meters.
More than 140 pieces of agricultural machinery and tools introduced and used by Heilongjiang Farm Reclamation over the years are on display here.
These agricultural machinery and farms have witnessed the development process of my country&#39;s agricultural modernization.
Leave a small home for everyone - Direct attack on mass transfer in Lianwei, Jiangkou River, Hefei, Anhui - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26th: Title: Leave a small home for everyone - Direct attack on mass transfer in Lianwei, Jiangkou River, Hefei, Anhui
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu and Liu Xiacun
At around 4 p.m. on July 25, Fu Kunbao, wearing muddy rubber shoes, walked back and forth from the front room to the back room, busy packing his things with his wife Zhou Yan.
&quot;I was still weeding in the field when I received the call from the village cadre to transfer.&quot;
Fu Kunbao said that he transferred more than 60 acres of land and planted rice, which is now growing well. &quot;I sprayed medicine yesterday, and I haven&#39;t packed away the tools or anything else.&quot;
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner, &quot;No one wants their home to be flooded, so let&#39;s sacrifice our small home for everyone.&quot;
In response to the continued high water pressure in Chaohu Lake and possible heavy rainfall, Hefei City, Anhui Province is preparing to activate the flood diversion and storage of the Jiangkou River Lianwei where Fu Kunbao&#39;s home is located on the 26th.
Jiangkou River Lianwei is located in Feixi County, close to the Chaohu Embankment.
Thousands of villagers from Yandian Township and Sanhe Town need to be relocated.
As of 16:00 on the 25th, the water level of Chaohu Lake, my country&#39;s fifth largest freshwater lake, remained at a high of 13.2 meters, 0.7 meters above the guaranteed water level.
The kitchen of Fu Kunbao&#39;s house is clean and tidy. There is a pot of pumpkin head vegetables on the table, and there are eggs and some braised vegetables in the refrigerator.
&quot;I didn&#39;t expect to move it. The water in Jiangkou River looks fine so far. &quot;
Zhou Yan said that her home is a bungalow and she has not yet decided where to put some large items.
&quot;Pack away your valuables first. Large items such as refrigerators and TVs can be temporarily placed at the homes of neighbors or relatives on higher ground.&quot;
Village cadre Wang Liwen gave Fu Kunbao advice.
Wang Liwen was responsible for the relocation and resettlement of 13 households of villagers. He notified each household one by one to confirm the resettlement plan for each person.
The nearest resettlement site to Fu Kunbao&#39;s home is Su Xiao Primary School in Yandian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to large items, Fu Kunbao and his wife also have more than 1,000 kilograms of grain and some newly purchased furniture that give Fu Kunbao and his wife a headache.
&quot;The food is going to be hauled to relatives&#39; houses, but there is no way to move the furniture.&quot;
After discussion, the couple put a stool under the newly purchased bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 p.m., Fu Kunbao started transporting things to relatives&#39; houses on a tricycle, while Zhou Yan continued to pack at home.
At about 11 o&#39;clock in the evening, the couple looked around at home, turned on the power switch, and prepared to go to the resettlement site.
&quot;I hope the water will recede soon.&quot;
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9:30 a.m. on July 26, reporters at the Jiangkou River Lianwei site saw that the local area had made preparations for flood diversion.
