Church fire in Nantes, France: Parish volunteer admits to arson
China News Service, July 26 (Xinhua) According to foreign media reports, on July 18, the famous Cathedral of St. Peter and St. Paul, a religious and historical architectural treasure in Nantes, France, was severely damaged in a fire, and the grand organ was completely destroyed.
On the 26th local time, the Nantes prosecutor announced that a parish volunteer responsible for security work in the cathedral had been charged with &quot;arson and destruction.&quot;
He has admitted that he lit the fire in the church.
According to the report, local prosecutor Senas said that the 39-year-old parish volunteer from Rwanda admitted that he lit three fires in the cathedral at night.
The man&#39;s lawyer said the arsonist now regrets what he did.
This person entered France through asylum a few years ago, was sheltered in the parish where the fire occurred, and was sheltered in the church.
The prosecutor pointed out that he recently tried to renew his visa and was in dialogue with the police station about this.
But the church said it still couldn&#39;t believe that this believer, who was usually very kind and smiling but didn&#39;t talk much, would destroy the church he loved so much.
On the day of the fire on July 18, the volunteer had already been questioned by the police because of illogical problems in his narrative, but he was later released.
The picture shows firefighters performing rescue operations at the scene.
On the evening of the 25th, as professional engineers from the Paris Central Police Laboratory obtained new evidence, this person was interrogated again.
This time, the man admitted to setting the fire.
According to reports, if convicted of intentional arson and destruction, the suspect may face 10 years in prison and a fine of 150,000 euros.
According to reports, the fire caused serious damage to the Cathedral of St. Pierre and St. Paul. The organ in the church was completely burned, and the stained glass window behind the organ was also severely damaged.
Brunet, the chief architect of French historic buildings, believes that it is conservatively estimated that the restoration work of Nantes Cathedral will take at least three years.
