According to reports, the area most severely affected by Hurricane Hanna is the area south of Corpus Christi to the mouth of the Rio Grande River, while widespread flash flooding may occur in the Rio Grande Valley.
Texas Governor Abbott said on the 25th: &quot;Any hurricane is a huge challenge.&quot;
Thirty-two counties in the state have entered a state of disaster emergency due to the hurricane.
Corpus Christi, a city with a population of more than 320,000, has closed its libraries and museums, and residents are on alert.
Abbott also said that at a time when Texas is being hit hard by the COVID-19 epidemic, this hurricane cannot be allowed to bring more casualties to Texas.
According to reports, precipitation in southern Texas is expected to reach 6 to 12 inches on the night of the 26th, and northern Texas and coastal Louisiana will also receive 3 to 5 inches of rain.
Due to factors such as global warming, &quot;Hanna&quot; formed earlier than previous Atlantic hurricane seasons.
Under normal circumstances, the first hurricane in the Atlantic usually doesn&#39;t form until mid-August.
Poland to withdraw from European treaty to prevent violence against women
Poland will take steps next week to withdraw from the European Treaty on the Prevention of Violence against Women, the Ministry of Justice said on Saturday.
Poland&#39;s right-wing government cabinet said the treaty violated the rights of parents by requiring schools to teach students about gender issues.
Polish Justice Minister Djoblo held a press conference and said that his Ministry of Justice will submit a request to the Ministry of Labor and Family on Monday to begin withdrawing from the treaty.
That treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
&quot;The treaty contains elements of an ideological nature that we consider to be harmful,&quot; Giobolo said.
Poland&#39;s ruling Law and Justice party and its coalition partners have a close alliance with the Roman Catholic Church and promote a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Andrzej Duda made hostility to gay rights one of the main issues during his successful re-election campaign this month.
Thousands of Poles, mostly women, protested in Warsaw and other cities on Friday against withdrawing from the convention.
Lempart, one of the organizers of the protest, said at a protest march in Warsaw that &quot;the purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to legalize domestic violence.&quot;
Some protesters held banners that read &quot;Law and Justice is hell for women.&quot;
Law and Justice has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland&#39;s previous centrist government ratified the convention in 2015.
The Law and Justice government says the treaty does not respect religion and requires liberal social policies to be taught in schools.
But so far the party has not decided to withdraw from the convention.
