FAA urgently orders inspection of 2,000 Boeing passenger planes due to possible engine stalling - Xinhuanet
The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring emergency inspections of approximately 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737 Classic passenger aircraft registered in the United States. The reason is that corrosion of the air check valves of the above-mentioned passenger aircraft may cause the engine to fly in the air. parking.
The FAA said it has received four reports of in-flight engine shutdowns of 737NG and 737 Classic passenger aircraft so far, and therefore issued emergency inspection requirements. The inspection targets are passenger aircraft that have been parked for seven consecutive days or more and those that have flown less than 11 times after being put back into flight. passenger plane.
The FAA warned that if the fifth-stage check valves on both engines of a passenger plane become corroded, they could become stuck in the open position, causing the plane to completely lose power and be unable to restart the engines.
The aviation regulator ordered that if corrosion is found in a check valve, air operators must replace the critical component before the aircraft can be put back into service.
Boeing responded later that day that the COVID-19 outbreak had led to reduced travel demand and that many passenger planes had been mothballed or used less often, making &quot;check valves more susceptible to corrosion.&quot;
Boeing also said that it has recommended that air operators inspect the passenger aircraft involved in the directive. If problems are found, Boeing will provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
The Associated Press reported that passenger planes owned by major U.S. airline operators usually fly multiple times a day, but after the outbreak of the new crown epidemic, a large number of passenger planes were grounded; as passenger travel demand has slowly increased recently, some passenger planes have returned to service.
The FAA did not release details of the four mid-air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines disclosed one of the incidents later on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its passenger planes was en route from Seattle, Washington to Austin, Texas, on July 15 when an engine suddenly stalled and the plane eventually made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the engine on that plane and had inspected the engines on six other planes in compliance with FAA orders.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines respectively said on the 24th that there were no engine stalls related to air check valves on their passenger planes.
Four passenger planes owned by American Airlines will be inspected, and 28 passenger planes owned by United Airlines will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect 20 of its passenger planes, but did not say whether engine stalls had occurred.
Multiple media reported that the FAA’s emergency airworthiness directive is another blow to Boeing.
A Boeing 737MAX passenger plane of Indonesian Lion Air and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019 respectively, killing a total of 346 people.
This series of passenger planes were subsequently grounded globally. Production was suspended in January this year and resumed in May.
FAA Administrator Steve Dickson admitted in June that the FAA &quot;made mistakes&quot; in supervising Boeing regarding the 737 MAX passenger aircraft.
