Hoh Xil Tibetan antelope enters migration season - Xinhuanet
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25 (Reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Conservation Station of the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration that monitoring showed that Tibetan antelopes had previously migrated to the Zhuonai Lake area in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth. The birthing process is ending and the cubs are returning to their original habitat.
Surveillance footage near the Wudaoliang Conservation Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelopes led three Tibetan antelope calves through the 3002-kilometer Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliang North Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. The Tibetan antelopes have begun to migrate back. .
Experts analyze that in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope calves in the migrating sheep has accounted for one-quarter to one-fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelopes.
Lian Xinming, associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, said: &quot;In the early stages of migration, Tibetan antelopes face a higher risk of being predated, so the number of cubs in the flock will be relatively small, or there may even be no cubs at all.&quot;
According to statistics from the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelopes migrating back is generally increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelopes migrating back was 4,860, an increase of 338 from 2018.
Lian Xinming said: &quot;This year&#39;s migration of Tibetan antelopes is expected to end in early September, and the number of Tibetan antelopes migrating back is still expected to continue to increase.&quot;
Tibetan antelope is a national first-level protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet, Altyn Mountains in Xinjiang and other places go to Zhuonai Lake in the hinterland of Hoh Xil to give birth to lambs.
Wu Xiaomin, an expert on the protection of Tibetan antelopes in my country and a researcher at the Shaanxi Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: &quot;The migration of Tibetan antelopes is a process in which female Tibetan antelopes return to their habitats with their cubs after giving birth. At first, they leave the country after giving birth. The migration group from Zedi is relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelopes will return to their respective habitats along different routes according to different geographical populations.&quot;
In order to ensure the safe return of the Tibetan antelope herds, the reporter learned that the Hoh Xil Management Office of the Yangtze River Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged staff to continue to carry out video monitoring and patrols in the main relocation areas.
If a herd of Tibetan antelopes is discovered trying to cross the highway, the mountain patrol team will immediately conduct temporary traffic control to allow the herds to pass through the wildlife passage safely and ensure that they are as little disturbed by humans as possible during their return journey.
So, how to relieve the heat in daily life?
Experts recommend that you try to avoid hot periods when going out in summer, and it is best not to walk or work under the scorching sun around noon, because the sun is strongest during this period and the possibility of heat stroke is higher.
If you must go out during this period, be sure to take protective measures, such as using a parasol, a sunhat, and sunglasses. If possible, apply sunscreen to prevent sunburn.
Try to choose light-colored, breathable cotton, linen, and silk clothes, and wear less chemical fiber clothes to avoid heat stroke due to inability to dissipate heat in time when sweating a lot.
In hot and muggy weather, prepare enough water and drink it in time. Do not wait until you are thirsty before drinking water, because once you feel thirsty, it means that your body is already dehydrated. Drink water at a temperature of 150 ml to 200 ml each time. Boil water, don’t drink ice water.
Depending on the temperature, the average person should drink 1.5 to 2 liters of water per day, and those working in high temperatures should drink 3 to 5 liters of water per day.
When you sweat a lot, you can add some salt water to make up for the salt your body loses due to sweating.
