Brazilian study shows hydroxychloroquine is ineffective in treating mild to moderate COVID-19 - China News
Recently, a Brazilian study showed that hydroxychloroquine is ineffective in patients with mild to moderate COVID-19.
The research report was published in the New England Journal of Medicine.
Pakistani researchers divided 667 patients from 55 hospitals across the country into three groups and conducted a clinical trial; they mainly compared the therapeutic effects of hydroxychloroquine alone or in combination with other antibiotics azithromycin, and analyzed whether it could help improve patients with mild and moderate COVID-19 pneumonia. condition.
The results show that hydroxychloroquine not only has no therapeutic effect, but may have damaging side effects on organs.
This study was conducted by a number of authoritative hospitals in Brazil, such as Hospital Israelita Albert Einstein, Hospital of Cardiology (HCor), Hospital Sírio-Libanês, etc., together with the Brazilian Clinical Research Institute (BCRI) and the Brazilian Institute of Critical Care Medicine. Done in conjunction with the Guardianship Research Network (BRICNet).
On the 25th local time, Brazilian President Jair Bolsonaro announced through social platforms that the result of the fourth nucleic acid test was negative.
