In the first half of this year, in the face of the impact of the COVID-19 epidemic, our country has coordinated efforts to promote epidemic prevention and control and economic and social development. The situation of epidemic prevention and control has continued to improve, the economy has been recovering steadily, and the performance of employment and prices, which are closely related to people&#39;s livelihood, has been generally stable. , the Chinese economy has handed over a warm economic performance report card.
The surveyed unemployment rate rose in the first two months of the year.
Especially in February, the production and operation activities of many enterprises were basically suspended. Enterprises&#39; labor demand decreased, recruitment was delayed or canceled, and the urban surveyed unemployment rate increased.
As the epidemic prevention and control situation gradually improves, the production and living order of the whole society continues to restore.
The Party Central Committee adheres to the general tone of seeking progress while maintaining stability, further intensifies macro-policy hedging, comprehensively strengthens employment priority policies, and actively promotes the work of assisting enterprises to stabilize jobs and expand employment.
my country has stepped up policies to stabilize jobs, implemented a policy combination of &quot;reductions, exemptions, deferrals, repayments, and subsidies&quot;. It has phased in reductions and exemptions for three social insurance unit payments, allowed deferral of social insurance premiums, and expanded unemployment insurance reimbursements for small, medium and micro enterprises to stabilize jobs, and work-for-work services. In order to benefit from the training policy, enterprises will be provided with recruitment subsidies and trainee subsidies for recruiting key groups into employment.
With the implementation of various employment stabilization policies, corporate labor demand has steadily rebounded, the employment situation has gradually improved, and the urban surveyed unemployment rate has gradually declined. In June, the surveyed unemployment rate was 5.7%.
Zhang Yi, director of the Population and Employment Statistics Department of the National Bureau of Statistics, said that in the second quarter, various employment policies continued to bear fruit, and the labor force that had withdrawn due to the impact of the epidemic in the early stage gradually returned. The urban labor participation rate in June increased by about 10 percentage points compared with February, which is consistent with It was close to the same level last year.
Data show that total urban employment in June increased by more than 19% compared with February, and most industries reached pre-epidemic levels; the average weekly working hours of enterprise employees reached 46.8 hours, 6.6 hours higher than February, and slightly higher than January by 0.1 hour.
Prices are also related to thousands of households.
In January this year, the CPI increased by 5.4% year-on-year, setting a new high in many years.
Entering February, although the year-on-year CPI increase has declined slightly, it is still in the &quot;5 range&quot;.
The year-on-year increase in CPI is at a high level, which is due to factors such as consumer demand before the Spring Festival, as well as factors such as the wrong month of the Spring Festival and a low year-on-year base.
However, the impact of the new coronavirus epidemic on prices is particularly obvious.
Affected by the epidemic prevention and control, logistics delays, untimely supply of materials, and increased transportation costs occurred across the country in January and February. In addition, some citizens hoarded and rushed to buy, and the prices of some daily necessities increased significantly.
In response to the disruption to the price situation caused by epidemic prevention and control, relevant departments have included important daily supplies into the scope of emergency transportation support to ensure smooth transportation of materials.
Under the influence of a series of policy measures, the market supply of vegetables and fruits has been effectively guaranteed.
In response to the rapid rise in pork prices at the beginning of this year, after the central government introduced policies to ensure supply and stabilize prices, all regions and departments quickly implemented them. The supply of pork reserves has significantly improved, pig production capacity has been restored in an orderly manner, and production and marketing order has gradually become normal.
Since March, pork prices have continued to decline, driving the year-on-year increase in food prices back to 10.6% in May. In June, affected by factors such as the slowdown in pig slaughter, reduced imports, and a rebound in collective consumer demand, pork prices rose slightly month-on-month.
Fresh vegetable prices have obvious seasonal changes, with an average increase of 3.4% in the first half of the year.
Affected by the high comparison base in the same period last year, fresh fruit prices continued to decline year-on-year, with an average decrease of 13.3% in the first half of the year.
The people&#39;s basic life is effectively guaranteed, and the overall economic and social situation remains stable and orderly.
As transportation and logistics gradually recover, various regions have stepped up efforts to ensure supply, and the market supply and demand situation has improved.
Since March, the CPI has declined for four consecutive months, and the year-on-year increase has also dropped from 4.3% in March to 2.5% in June. The overall price level has returned to stability.
In the second half of the year, my country&#39;s prices will continue to remain at a moderate level and the overall inflationary pressure will be small. However, it is still necessary to promote the restoration of production and living order on the premise of normalizing epidemic prevention and control.
Effectively respond to natural disasters such as floods and droughts in the main production areas of grain, fruits and vegetables, and other agricultural products, strengthen market supervision, and resolutely crack down on hoarding, price gouging and other behaviors that disrupt market order.
