A 3-year-old child was hit while playing on the college playground. Is it reasonable to sue the school after receiving compensation?
2020-07-26 05:01:11 Source: Legal Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
The playground was smashed, the children will sue the school after receiving compensation
□ Our correspondent Zhao Yifan
When 3-year-old Xiao Wen was playing on the playground of a university, he was accidentally hit in the head by Chen from the softball team while pitching.
After Chen paid compensation, Xiaowen&#39;s father, Mr. Wen, acted as Xiaowen&#39;s legal representative and sued the school to the court, demanding that the school where the playground where the incident occurred apologize, apologize, and pay a total of 20,000 yuan in medical expenses and solitary payments for mental damage.
Recently, the Beijing Haidian District People&#39;s Court heard the case and held that the school had set up a protective net on the playground at the time of the incident and had fulfilled its appropriate safety obligations, and that Chen had paid compensation. Based on this judgment, the plaintiff&#39;s case was dismissed. Claims.
Mr. Wen complained that during the summer vacation of 2019, he took Xiao Wen to play on the school playground, while the softball team was training on the playground.
In order to avoid the risks caused by this, Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents stayed in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then Chen, a member of the softball team, let go while throwing the ball, causing the softball to fly over the protective net into the above-mentioned safe area and hit the back of Xiaowen&#39;s head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiaowen to the hospital for treatment, and he was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen believes that the school’s stadium facilities do not comply with relevant safety regulations, and the team and related facilities are not effectively managed.
The school&#39;s negligence led to the occurrence of the above incident, which caused Xiaowen to suffer great physical and mental pain and also brought great pain to his family. The school should bear legal responsibility for this.
In this regard, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net on the playground and posted management regulations and training notices, informing them that they must keep a safe distance from the training ground when entering the playground and reminding them to pay attention to their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school &quot;failed to do so&quot; &quot;Safety protection obligation&quot;, so we do not agree to compensation.
After the trial, the court held that the venue where the incident occurred was a venue open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school had safety guarantee obligations for the management of the playground, this safety guarantee obligation only required a general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net on the playground and fulfilled its appropriate safety obligations. Chen also compensated Xiaowen for more than 2,000 yuan in medical expenses, transportation expenses and other losses in accordance with the previously reached compensation agreement. Both parties It was agreed that the dispute would be resolved once and for all.
Afterwards, Xiaowen&#39;s parents once again claimed compensation from the school, but there was no legal basis for it. The court ruled to reject all the plaintiff&#39;s claims.
After the verdict was announced, neither party appealed, and the verdict is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of my country&#39;s Tort Liability Law, as the manager of a public place, the school has the obligation to ensure safety; if the behavior of a third party causes damage to others, the third party shall bear tort liability and fails to ensure safety. Managers of public places with obligations shall bear corresponding supplementary responsibilities.
The judge said that as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to understand the actual situation of the entire place, foresee possible dangers and damages, and is therefore most likely to take necessary measures to prevent the occurrence of losses or reduce the extent of the damage, and to avoid and mitigate the damage. The cost of damage is the lowest, so the law stipulates that they should bear the corresponding protection obligations when engaging in social activities.
In this case, for unspecified groups of people entering a playground that is open to the public free of charge, the school’s safety protection obligations should be commensurate with the social activities it engages in. Specifically, it should take basic safety measures and protect against hidden dangers. Have a duty to inform.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on managers of public places.
If the school has set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be determined that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal responsibility.
In addition, for third-party infringement, even if the managers of schools and other public places fail to fulfill their safety protection obligations, the liability they bear is a supplementary form of damage compensation. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, after the managers bear supplementary liability, You can also seek compensation from a third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, the victim should not expand the scope of claims after having received compensation from the direct tortfeasor.
