Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated epidemics-China News
2020-07-26 04:56:44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sishuo Editor: Wang Sishuo
Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated epidemics
In the early days of the COVID-19 outbreak, Israel&#39;s prevention and control measures were effective.
However, as prevention and control measures are gradually lifted, the number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli government has taken emergency measures many times to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of COVID-19 was confirmed in Israel. It quickly took measures to close all entry and exit ports, suspend non-essential industries, switch schools to online teaching, restrict public transportation and non-essential social activities, and blockade cities with severe epidemics. Military and police jointly maintain prevention and control measures, etc.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results. By mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of new coronavirus pneumonia in Israel in a single day dropped to single digits.
With the epidemic under control and various prevention and control measures in Israel being fully lifted, the number of new confirmed cases of COVID-19 has gradually rebounded since June.
Especially since July, the spread of the epidemic has continued to accelerate.
In recent days, the daily number of new cases in Israel has exceeded 1,500 on eight days. As of press time on July 25, the number of new cases that day reached 916.
As of July 25, Israel had 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
Faced with the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli government has taken emergency measures many times to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other public entertainment venues, and also introduced a policy to restrict public transportation, stipulating that each bus should not have more than 20 passengers. .
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictive measures, including the implementation of &quot;city closures&quot; on weekends, stipulating that the &quot;city closures&quot; will be implemented from 17:00 every Friday to 5:00 every Sunday.
During this period, people can go out, but shops, shopping malls, barber shops, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition halls, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while basic service places such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open. .
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all dates and periods, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes are prohibited from dine-in, and only takeaway services are allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people did not pay enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and failed to form a joint force with the government in fighting the epidemic.
After the recurrence of the epidemic in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest because the government&#39;s prevention and control measures affected their economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people held a demonstration in Tel Aviv, believing that anti-epidemic policies would affect the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands more protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu’s official residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu’s promulgation of prevention and control measures such as banning dine-in restaurants and cafes without providing corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people do not comply with regulations such as wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters during outdoor activities. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing masks, many people only wear masks on their chins or hang them on their wrists.
During the recurring epidemic, schools were hardest hit by the spread of the new coronavirus. According to a recent visit to this kindergarten, reporters found that teachers and students in the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other. This caused a large number of teachers and students to Infection with viruses poses hidden dangers.
Professor Eli Waxman, a member of the Israeli National Security Council’s Expert Advisory Group on Combating the Epidemic, believes that Israel is heading towards a “dangerous situation” and points out that the current epidemic prevention and control measures taken by Israel are not enough and that all leisure and entertainment venues and summer holidays should be closed. schools to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to fight the epidemic. The parliament and various government departments should abandon their own interests as soon as possible, reach an agreement on fighting the epidemic, and formulate clear steps including relevant restrictions in different departments.
