At Banong Zhuokang sentry point, platoon leader Yu Wang and a soldier were on guard duty.
In this place where the annual average temperature is more than ten degrees below zero, a row of simple barracks stands at the mountain pass. Not far from the barracks, a national flag flutters in the wind. The soldiers stand guard in the wind every day, and they also need to regularly patrol to higher altitude locations. .
The soldiers climbed up the steep slope of the rocks and had to use both hands and feet.
It was late July, a time when flowers and plants flourished at lower altitudes, but in Banong Chokhang, only the ravine behind the barracks had relatively dense green.
Gao Peng, a soldier who has been stationed at the sentry point for six years, pointed to the ravine and said that this is their back garden. Only in July and August every year can you see the grass growing slowly. Soon after, it all turns yellow and is covered with snow.
Patrolling on foot may take about 9 hours.
In the harsh plateau environment, the soldiers stationed here are in the company of snow-capped mountains and glaciers all year round, and they have to regularly patrol mountain passes at higher altitudes.
A few days ago, a patrol team composed of 8 soldiers, led by instructor Liang Yixin, once again embarked on the patrol road.
Each soldier carries about 30 kilograms of weight and sets off to the target point early in the morning.
On the way, a soldier had a high voltage, and his comrades rushed to rescue him.
